 stunning of animals before slaughter. Despite claims to the contrary, this study offers clear evidence of underlying, unrelenting antisemitic motivations in the prosecutions, and highlights the ways in which a basic idea of innate Jewish cruelty was always juxtaposed with an overtly Christian ideal of humane treatment of animals across time and borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal rights movementvCase studies. 0aAnimal rights movementxCase studies. 0aLivestockxStunningvCase studies. 0aLivestockxStunningxCase studies. 0aMeat industry and tradexLaw and legislationvCase studies. 0aMeat industry and tradexLaw and legislationxCase studies. 0aReligious discriminationxLaw and legislationvCase studies. 0aReligious discriminationxLaw and legislationxCase studies. 0aShehitahvCase studies. 0aShehitahxCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aJewish method of slaughter.  aShechita.  aabattoirs.  aanimal cruelty.  aantisemitism.  ahumane societies.  akashrut.  ashochet.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068818440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618117434zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618117434423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781618117434.jpg  a978-3-11-068818-4  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK